06162nam a22007935i 9789048544561DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485445617 a10.1515/97890485445612doi  a(DE-B1597)585496  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aART0150802bisacsh00aPortrait Cultures of the Early Modern Cardinal /ced. by Irene Brooke, Piers Baker-Bates. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (390 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVisual and Material Culture, 1300 -170000tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIllustrations -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Cardinals and their Images -- t1. Portraying the Princes of the Church -- t2. The Early Modern Cardinal -- tPart I - Individuality and Identity: Florence and Rome -- t3. Visual and Verbal Portraits of Cardinals in Fifteenth-Century Florence -- t4. Dead Ringers: Cardinals and their Effigies, 1400-1520 -- tPart II - Divided Loyalties: Venice and Rome -- t5. The Role of Cardinals' Portraits in Venice: The Case of the Grimani Family and Some Thoughts on the Correr MS Morosini Grimani 270 -- t6. Role Playing: Cardinals in Historical Action in Leandro Bassano's Honorius III Approving the Rule of St. Dominic in 1216 and the War of the Interdict -- tPart III - Collecting and Display: Portraits and Worldly Goods -- t7. Renaissance Cardinals and Pontifical Mules -- t8. Portraits as Symbols: Cardinals' Portraits in the Roman and Local Collections of Some Counter-Reformation Cardinals -- t9. Portraits as a Sign of Possession: Cardinals and their Protectorships in Early Modern Rome -- tPart IV - Post-Tridentine Piety: The Devout Cardinal -- t10. Group Portraits of Cardinal Bembo and his Friends in the Wake of Trent -- t11. Two Cardinal Portraits by Scipione Pulzone in the Harvard Art Museums and their Related Versions -- t12. Miracle-Working Portraits of a Cardinal Saint: Managing the Devotional Medals of San Carlo Borromeo -- tConclusion: Cardinal Portraits beyond Italy -- t13. Portraying the Ideal Spanish Tridentine Prelate -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe visual legacy of early modern cardinals constitutes a vast and extremely rich body of artworks, many of superb quality, in a variety of media, often by well-known artists and skilled craftsmen. Yet cardinal portraits have primarily been analysed within biographical studies of the represented individual, in relation to the artists who created them, or within the broader genre of portraiture. No more profound investigation of these as a specific category of object has ever been attempted. This volume addresses questions surrounding the production, collection, and status of the cardinal portrait, covering diverse geographies and varied media. Examining the development of cardinals' imagery in terms of their multi-layered identities, this volume considers portraits of 'princes of the Church' as a specific cultural phenomenon reflecting cardinals' unique social and political position.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aCardinals, Early Modern, Portrait, Catholic Church, Portraiture.1 aBaker-Bates, Piers, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBates, Piers, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooke, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooke, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarrabino, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul